Author::::<a href="http://social.ndtv.com/groups.php?id=739889" target="_blank">PB Sharma</a>

Comment::::<div class="com_user_text">
                            The article by IITDelhi Professor Rukmi Bhaya has made a case for LEAF (Liberal Education in the Arts Fields) in IITs. While I fully appreciate and acknowledge the value and worth of liberal arts I do not subscribe to beating its drum too much in our engineering and technology education system that is driven by the strength of STEM, Science, Technology, Engineering and Maths. The only new addition is biotechnology  and biological sciences. <br/><br/>
Let me share with you my experience during my studies in UK in 1970s. At that time the drums of liberal arts were being echoed as being important to create the human face of science and engineering. The emotional appeal was so strong for liberal arts at that time in universities in the west that  it drove the younger generation away from STEM. The net result was a rapid decline in interest for mathematics and science even at school levels let alone at the university. <br/><br/>
Thank God that the western universities were able to draw immense talent in STEM from India and other eastern countries where love for mathematics and science was so profound that the younger generation was keen to explore the realms of science and the joy of engineering and technology in company of the great science and technology minds of learned professors and practitioners in great western universities and in the R&amp;D organisations and corporates.<br/><br/>
Even today the western world is at a loss to understand as to how to bring back the love for science and joy of mathematics back into its schools and universities.<br/><br/>
Compared to this, mathematics is the foundation of India's rich and profound spiritual civilisation and science, vigyana, is the body fluid of Indian way of life. As such the natural love for STEM from school to university levels in India is something both natural to our scientific spiritual civilisation and we should be proud that this craze for STEM continues to drive India's landscape of education, higher education included.<br/><br/>
 I would therefore suggest that rather than beating the drum of LEAF ( Liberal Education in the Arts Field) we should integrate humanities and arts in STEM to make it STEAM (Science, Technology,Engineering, Arts and Mathematics). In any case, the human interface of science and technology is today more important than ever before as we have the monumental challenge of creating a better and brighter tomorrow by creating energy in plenty, moping out the monstrous  environmental pollution (land, water and air), wiping out poverty and hunger by creating millions and millions of jobs and enterprises, all this requires a more profound commitment to STEAM.<br/><br/>
As a former professor of IIT Delhi, I have tremendous pride in the goodness created by the IITs for India and for the great nations of the world. Let us not forget this pride created by the IITians is primarily because of their sustained focus on creativity and innovativeness of science, engineering and technology on the strength of STEM and not the liberal education in arts field, LEAF. Let the new generation not undermine the value and worth of STEM or better STEAM for creating a better tomorrow for India and the humanity at large.<br/><br/>
Professor PB Sharma<br/>
Vice-Chancellor, Amity University Gurgaon<br/>
Founder Vice-Chancellor, Delhi Technological University<br/>
Former Professor of Mechanical Engineering, IIT Delhi
                         </div>



